  "text": "At the age of 4 she presented failure to thrive (Weight= -3.3 SDS; Height= -4.2 SDS), microcephaly, severe development delay, muscle weakness, epilepsy, diabetes mellitus ( Figure 1 ) and was classified as full DEND syndrome [CITATION_1] . A novel C166Y mutation in KCNJ11 was found by sequencing of the patient's KCNJ11 gene using genomic DNA extracted from peripheral lymphocytes by standard methods [CITATION_2] . Figure 1 . Four-year old child with DEND syndrome due to a C166Y mutation in KCNJ11 (Kir6.2). Note severe development delay, limb spasticity and failure to thrive. tent hyperglycemia occurring within the first 6 months of life, lasting more than 2 weeks and requiring insulin therapy [CITATION_3] , and accordingly to the subsequent clinical course, it will be classified as permanent or transient [CITATION_4] .",
